<br>
It detailed a way of building 2001 type rotating stations automatically in orbit with the minumum of human involvement.<br>
<br>
For $400 billion you would get a 200 metre diameter station in Earth orbit, another in Mars orbit and a 3rd station acting as a cycling ship between Earth annd Mars.<br>
<br>
Basically, you used automatic wrapping machines to wrap an inflatable core with aluminium sheets until you had a cylinder with the required wall thickness. During construction, humans would only be needed to change the rolls of aluminium.<br>
<br>
Anybody else read this article and if so what do you think of the idea? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 108<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/15/03 10:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=963.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   2001 type rotating space stations</span><hr size=1> Orbiting 'Wheel house&quot; space stations or spin sphere al la O'Neil have been around since the 50's. Personally, I see nothing wrong with them, they provide angular momentum thus gravity but that said. <br>
<br>
They require more building materials compared to cheap &quot;Tin can&quot; habitats. I guess, they have steel foam  and composites etc. that could work. But again, the age old problem of providing enough power to maintain a level of rotation that will provide enough gravity to make the venture worthwhile so as not to make humans too sick with inner ear motion.<br>
 <br>
You can't expect humans to take a Dramamine tabs every minute.<br>
 <br>
Diameter of station must be large enough to keep a crew with a comfortable level of motion and gravity. This is expensive to power, energy wise and it would have to be nuclear reactor type, providing the power necessary for the station's constant power demand requirements. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 455<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/28/03 3:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=963.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   ????</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; problem of providing enough power to maintain a level of rotation that<br>
will provide enough gravity<br>
&gt; This is expensive to power, energy wise and it would have to be nuclear<br>
reactor type, providing the power necessary for the station's constant<br>
power demand requirements.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 I don't see what you're thinking of. What power requirement to keep it spinning?<br>
Certainly, there's some kind of energy released to start it spinning, but once it's there, it kees going.<br>
 The power to spin-up or down can come from aany of many sources. Flywheels are suggested: use solar power to spin up flywheels, and then clutch them to the station. As the station spins up, the wheels lose energy to it. To spin down, send the spin energy back to the flywheels.<br>
Rockets can be used also. Yes, there's delta-V and propellant to be concerned with, but it's not that much (a tiny fraction of what's required to get the entire station mass moving at a velocity similar to the rim speed).<br>
Solar thermal with water reaction mass works, as do ion jets, pellet throwers, etc.<br>
In regards to momentum-exchange tethers (rotavators for throwing payloads) it's found that a tether can &quot;pump up&quot; it's spin without reaction mass -reeling in &amp; out the ends of the rope, like a child on a swing. They can even raise their perigee this way, by taking energy away from their orbital energy, thereby lowering their apogee.<br>
<br>
As to maintaining power for the station while it's spinning, it's nothing. Contra-rotating solar panels at the axis, or simply attached to the non-spun sections (along with airlocks and docking ports).<br>
Space probes since the early days have used spin to maintain even heating and solar panels either don't spin or are plastered around the outside so they catch sun from any direction. Similarly commo antennae pointing and even firing jets to alter course or pointing aren't a problem.<br>
<br>
this station type goes back far beyond Kubrick's movie.<br>
<br>
http://www.astronautix.com/craft/noordung.htm<br>
1928 book laid out the requirements pretty well. I can't find the side-view image which shows the mirrors and boiler pipes for powering generators.<br>
