<br>
Uh...I believe you've missed the notion: Energy is not free. You have to provide energy one way or another whether your spinning space station is in orbit half way to alpha centuri from our Sun or in orbit at L2, L5 etc. There is a penalty namely: external tidal gravity, internal sources and drag due in small part to solar wind. Every object in our Universe &quot;Neck of the woods&quot; pays for this feature. Natural celestial objects initially have already been provided with the necessary power eons ago but they also pay a little price called orbital degradation over time this also includes man made objects in space we are no different.<br>
<br>
The laws that govern this are Newton's 2nd law of motion and Laws of thermodynamics and some others.<br>
<br>
This does not include incidentals, if you know anything about nuclear submarines as well as ships or for that matter your car. Sometimes you have to stop spinning your wheels and halt for a red light or brake for an Emergency. <br>
You have to add power to spin up your station and also to provide power for life support systems more that lets say a human habitat on planet X.<br>
<br>
Solar panel systems require, Square area of space structure therefore mass and torque limitations not to mention photon line of sight and distance limitations to power solar receptors to power your station. Limitations not a factor with smaller space borne high energy density dynamic fast nuclear reactors with lightweight shielding, one limitation would be that you would have to replace the spent fuel but again this wouldn't be a problem on planet X with the necessary radioactive isotopes or transuranics available for fuel and safe operating shielding material... maybe you find water and ice mud on planet X.<br>
<br>
Look... maybe a spinner outpost station might be useful between star systems but around the solar system with tons of basalt regolith swirling about us who needs 2001 Kubrick...don't get me wrong. I like Hollywood stuff but it's just too sexy pretty to be real in space in the short term.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 456<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/31/03 12:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=963.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: spinner space colonies a la 1974 O'Neill</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://lifesci3.arc.nasa.gov/SpaceSettlement/70sArt/AC76-0525q.jpeg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
