As to this danger, and the bit about&quot; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>a human habitat on planet X.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
You seem to imply that a spinning station is more difficult than a planet-based colony?<br>
The <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://lifesci3.arc.nasa.gov/SpaceSettlement/75SummerStudy/Design.html">'70s NASA studies</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> on space settlements disagree.<br>
Everything's easier in space. You simply cannot get appropriate gravity on another body, and you cannot ignore it or say that we'll find ways to work around low-gravity.<br>
Everything from energy and raw materials acquisition, production, handling, and transport to/from the colony, to human factors is better done in space.<br>
 <br>
They designed these space colonies to be immediately comfortable to people as they are now, with no new inventions needed.<br>
<br>
The &quot;tons of basalt&quot; you cite is actually the equivalent of the protection we on Earth recieve from space radiation at about 1 mile above sea level. About 5 tonnes of mass of atmosphere lie above each square meter (not air pressure, but mass in direct line above).<br>
<br>
More like 100 million tons of regolith -about 1.7 meter of reinforced concrete for the colony hull.<br>
And before you hurt ourself laughing, tell it to MIT, NASA Ames and JPL, Stanford, and everybody else who's looked hard at their findings.<br>
<br>
 For information about the advantages of living in a spinning colony as opposed to &quot;planet X&quot;, see Mike Comb's excellent Space Settlement <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.geocities.com/CapeCanaveral/Lab/9917/spacsetl.htm">FAQ</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I like Hollywood stuff but it's just too sexy pretty to be real in space in the short term. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 I don't like hollywood stuff mostly. Too fake, too reliant on rubber science, too little cognizant to the realistic possibilities in space.<br>
The station in &quot;2001&quot; or any number of other spinning stations concepts are fine short term (Actually, Kubric/Clarke's station is more likely too big to be built from Earth-launched materials. More likely space resources. Look into the various proposals to use spent fuel tanks as habitats (some of which approach the one in the movie in size).<br>
In the '70s, NASA did real hard economics and engineering studies on the habitability of space. Using readily understood technologies, the biggest colony they defined in detail was 2 contra-rotating cylinders, 4.5 miles diameter, 20 miles long.<br>
<br>
Besides, who's talking only about the near-term? You mentioned other planets and between the stars -other planets aren't likely to be any more &quot;terrestrial&quot; than, say, Mars or Titan. Space colonies could be anywhere from the orbit of Mercury out way past Neptune or interstellar space (with a big enough mirror), and around any star, of any size, color, or type (mirrors and filtering layers).<br>
We don't need to find &quot;habitable&quot; planets (we probably won't) because with simple materials available <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>anywhere in this universe</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> we can build habitats entirely suitable to contemporary Earth life.<br>
<br>
At this one, look for the appendices about design requirements, and &quot;Chapter 3 - Human Needs In Space&quot;<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Orbital Space Settlements (NASA Ames)<br>
