I remember back around new-years 2000-2001, a big newspaper article talked about the comparison between the movie and reality.<br>
 I think it was Ben Bova who bemoaned the fact that we haven't even flown a single artificial G test mission.<br>
<br>
 Which brings me to the plug:<br>
 I like to point out that the Mars Society, with (millions of dollars of) entirely private funding, has conducted programs which are vital if we ever plan to go, and which the government monopoly space program hasn't done in the 30 or so years since they proved it possible.<br>
Pascal Lee of NASA Ames said that his experiences in the first <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.marssociety.org/arctic/index.asp">F-MARS</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> crew (the analogue Mars exploration outpost the Society put on Devon Island) were very illuminating. NASA teams which have used Haughton meteorite crater on the island always wrked out of tents, and operated like any other arctic expedition. The F-MARS crews practise as if they were on Mars: spending time in a designated &quot;airlock&quot; inside the hab as if they were breathing down (to eliminate N2 from thier bloodstreams), and always wearing suits when outside the Hab, and using a time delay on all communications with &quot;Earth&quot;. Simply wearing the costume suits was a lesson: You can't hear anything outside, you're wearing snowmobile gloves at all times and the suit won't let you bend over or even easily see the ground at your feet!<br>
It really changes your estimation of difficulty and EVA time required to perform a task.<br>
<br>
